    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1448294216,
    "creation_date" : 1448294216,
    "answer_id" : 33875232,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>For me the issue was a conflict between several versions of the same library. The Eclipse assist was using an older version than maven. </p>\n\n<p>I had to go to the .m2 directory and delete the unwanted lib version + restart eclipse.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 327482,
      "reputation" : 1408,
      "user_id" : 649890,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 74,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7bb2a4199978e261981e948f7047e547?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "arnehehe",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/649890/arnehehe"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1449044868,
    "creation_date" : 1449044868,
    "answer_id" : 34037977,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In my case, Intellisense had only disappeared in a few classes in one project. It turned out this was because of a missing library on the build path (although it worked previously).</p>\n\n<p>So definitely check all the errors or problems in Eclipse and try to find if a library may be missing</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6730698,
      "reputation" : 121,
      "user_id" : 6117074,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/10206028596527076/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Tom Orsi",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6117074/tom-orsi"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1642012648,
    "last_edit_date" : 1642012648,
    "creation_date" : 1465326338,
    "answer_id" : 37687375,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I ran into this and it ended up being I was opening the file with the text editor and not the java editor.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 404573,
      "reputation" : 7956,
      "user_id" : 772981,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 46,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fc5e6ffb24a245e2e55b0b3ff2e539df?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Jarekczek",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/772981/jarekczek"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1478450075,
    "creation_date" : 1478450075,
    "answer_id" : 40451743,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I experience problems on Eclipse Neon when <strong>editing a file which does not belong to the project directory</strong>. When I copy the same file to the project root directory, not even to the src directory, the completion starts working.</p>\n\n<p>When the file is opened from a different directory, only completion for JRE works. That is for example: <code>java.</code> completes, but <code>junit.</code> does not.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9337303,
      "reputation" : 10573,
      "user_id" : 6931119,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 89,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b7e2f7b738016a6dbb35530e611a178e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Witold Kaczurba",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6931119/witold-kaczurba"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1484125288,
    "creation_date" : 1484125288,
    "answer_id" : 41586552,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Once you have you configuration checked and completion is still not working:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>make sure you have the right directory structure.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Do you see the right icon beside the file?:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/vGNoP.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/vGNoP.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>It will tell you how the file will be treated by Eclipse:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/hHHgf.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/hHHgf.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>I am posting this answer as I had that story with with Maven webapp artifact. By default Maven-WebApp does not create folder for sources and I put my Java into resources, wondering for 5 minutes what was going on... :)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 9040200,
        "reputation" : 271,
        "user_id" : 6734725,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 67,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a3ad8274dfe9266b08718d4bcdaf9dc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "J-ho",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6734725/j-ho"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1561961054,
      "post_id" : 44603092,
      "comment_id" : 100213443,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "This may make your eclipse very slow with big code base."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3008908,
      "reputation" : 2943,
      "user_id" : 2552811,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 76,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c24e601c8aca1a57934e9219ceeb3704?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Hoa Vu",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2552811/hoa-vu"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 51,
    "last_activity_date" : 1497692723,
    "creation_date" : 1497692723,
    "answer_id" : 44603092,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In case someone comes here and want to activate the autocomplete function, go to</p>\n\n<p><code>Preferences -&gt; Java -&gt; Editor -&gt; Content Assist.</code> </p>\n\n<p>Then in the <strong>Auto Activation</strong> section fill in <strong>Auto activation triggers</strong> for Java: </p>\n\n<pre><code>abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ._\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/d4vOQ.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/d4vOQ.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3586822,
      "reputation" : 414,
      "user_id" : 2993812,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/39BJZ.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "tetebueno",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2993812/tetebueno"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1513876149,
    "creation_date" : 1513876149,
    "answer_id" : 47929685,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Just in case anyone got to a desperate point where nothing works... It happened to us that the content assist somehow shrunk so no suggestion was shown, just the \"Press Ctrl+Space for non-Java...\" could be seen.\nSo, it was just a matter of dragging the corner of the content assist to enlarge the pop-up.</p>\n\n<p>I know, embarrassing. Hope it helps.</p>\n\n<p>Note: this was an Ubuntu server with Xfce4 using Eclipse Oxygen.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9973808,
      "reputation" : 63,
      "user_id" : 7379069,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1886a5ee5a43146594d5f449546700f7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Togepi",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7379069/togepi"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1516804885,
    "last_edit_date" : 1516804885,
    "creation_date" : 1516804410,
    "answer_id" : 48424945,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Maybe this helps other people who come across the same issue.</p>\n\n<p>My setup: old Gradle project (version Gradle 2.12) made by someone else, imported using the Gradle Import Wizard into STS (Eclipse Oxygen.2 (4.7.2)).</p>\n\n<p>Code completion did not work either (and I still have hollow Js at the Java files), but at least I got the code completion to work by doing:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>right click on the project folder > Properties > Gradle > Configure Workspace Settings > Java > Editor > Content Assist > Advanced</li>\n<li>check \"Java Proposals in upper window.</li>\n<li>2x Apply &amp; Close</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 203484,
        "reputation" : 165,
        "user_id" : 574872,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9d28959256ff4cf87f27ab17014e7faa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "signonsridhar",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/574872/signonsridhar"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1565826339,
      "post_id" : 56425302,
      "comment_id" : 101475375,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Yes for me i am unable to browse the java methods, click browse/open declaration is not working. And this is happening quite frequently, the java class files have effectively become text files. So i keep deleting the workspace and import the maven project, back into action in a minute."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9130923,
      "reputation" : 2269,
      "user_id" : 6792588,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8e081456a4b051ad81d557d672db8fa0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Naor Bar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6792588/naor-bar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1559557150,
    "creation_date" : 1559557150,
    "answer_id" : 56425302,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>For those who use the latest 3-19 eclipse build:</strong></p>\n\n<p>It just happened to me when upgrading from <strong>Oxygen</strong> to <strong>3-19</strong> eclipse version, so I assume the auto-complete feature does not migrated correctly during the upgrade process.</p>\n\n<p>The only solution that worked for me was to create a new eclipse workspace, and import the project/s to it. It might take a few minutes, but it worth it - comparing to the time spent on other solutions... </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 379606,
      "reputation" : 6642,
      "user_id" : 733092,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/DAX12.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Noumenon",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/733092/noumenon"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1580861865,
    "creation_date" : 1580861865,
    "answer_id" : 60067364,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you're experiencing this in an enum, or when initializing an array with anonymous classes, it's a known bug in Eclipse. See <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47481597/eclipse-content-assist-not-working-in-enum-constant-parameter-list\">Eclipse content assist not working in enum constant parameter list</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5628358,
      "reputation" : 137,
      "user_id" : 4455993,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/x9l3G.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Bill Snee",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4455993/bill-snee"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1586905168,
    "creation_date" : 1586905168,
    "answer_id" : 61218644,
    "question_id" : 908489,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I have run into this problem since upgrading to Eclipse 2019-09.  Based on some of the suggestions above, this is what worked for me.</p>\n\n<p>I had to go to Eclipse -> Preferences -> Java -> Editor -> Content Assist -> Advanced.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/f8UCl.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/f8UCl.png\" alt=\"Java Editor/Content Assist Advanced\"></a></p>\n\n<p>I found out that if I turn on any of the key binding proposals, Java Non-Type, Java, Java (Task-Focused) or Java Type proposal, then I was able to use auto complete.  If I turned them all on, then not only did auto complete work, but I got duplicate methods listed.  I am guessing, but I will probably used Java Type Proposals.  Any clarification of what differs for these four types would be appreciated.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
